## Typography — Treat It Like a Design Element

Typography on award-winning sites does structural work, not just labeling.

- Headlines must be large. Uncomfortably large. Try clamp(3rem, 10vw, 9rem).
- Use variable fonts where possible — weight, width, optical size.
- Mix weights intentionally: ultra-heavy display + light body is a system.
- Tracking on uppercase labels: 0.15em–0.25em minimum.
- Line height on large type: 0.9–1.05 (tighter than you think).
- Never use system fonts for display text. Pick a Google Font or variable font
  that has personality. Name it in the direction checkpoint.
- Type can be a texture: large background letterforms, oversized numbers,
  masked text reveals — use these before reaching for decorative graphics.

---

## Color — Restraint With One Moment of Intensity

Award sites rarely use many colors. They use few colors with total commitment.

- Pick a foundation: true black (#0a0a0a), warm off-white (#f5f0eb),
  deep navy, slate, or bone. Not "background: white", not "bg-gray-100".
- Pick ONE accent. Not two. Make it electric against the foundation.
  Good examples: acid green on black, raw amber on near-white, bone on black.
- Semantic color only for functional elements (errors, success). Not decoration.
- Gradients only when they serve the spatial narrative (depth, light source).
  Never gradient-as-decoration.
- If using dark mode: deep surfaces have subtle warmth or coolness, 
  never pure neutral gray stacks.

---

## Motion — The Invisible Layer That Separates Good From Great

Without motion, a site is a poster. With it, it breathes.

- Every page entrance: elements should arrive, not appear.
  Minimum: staggered fade + translate on load (GSAP or CSS).
- Scroll behavior: at least one element that responds to scroll position.
  Parallax text, pinned sections, horizontal scroll, progress-driven opacity.
- Hover states are micro-stories: don't just change color. Change scale +
  color + a secondary element simultaneously.
- Use CSS custom properties to drive animation values from JS for
  cursor-reactive effects (magnetic buttons, cursor trails, spotlight).
- Implement with: GSAP (preferred), Framer Motion, or CSS @keyframes.
  Never use transition: all.

---

## Layout — Break the Grid Intentionally

Generic AI UI uses 12-column grids with equal gutters everywhere.
Award-level work knows when to destroy the grid for effect.

- Establish a grid first (CSS Grid, named areas). Then intentionally violate
  it in 1–2 places: a bleed element, an oversized type block, an asymmetric
  split.
- Use extreme aspect ratios for visual interest: 16:9, 21:9, 1:2 panels.
- Whitespace is active, not empty. Large whitespace = presence, not laziness.
- Horizontal scroll sections for portfolios/carousels — not vertical grids.
- Overlapping elements create depth without shadows: z-index as a design tool.
- Consider full-viewport sections that each tell one story (scroll-snapped
  or scroll-triggered, like shader.se).

---

## Texture & Depth — Without Defaulting to Shadows

Shadows are the lazy path to depth. Award sites use:

- Grain/noise overlays (SVG feTurbulence or CSS noise) at 2–5% opacity
  for tactility.
- Subtle mesh or gradient backgrounds as an atmospheric layer.
- Glass morphism only when it has a real surface behind it — not floating
  glass over white.
- Border as surface edge: 1px border at 8–12% opacity defines a plane
  without drop shadows.
- Background canvas elements: WebGL, Three.js, or even pure CSS for
  ambient motion (particle fields, shader gradients, flowing meshes).
  If the project allows it, suggest and implement a canvas background.

